<p>A <b>Software Requirements Specification</b> (<b>SRS</b>) is a complete description of the behavior of the system to be developed. It includes a set of <a href="/wiki/Use_case" title="Use case">use cases</a> that describe all the interactions the users will have with the software. Use cases are also known as <a href="/wiki/Functional_requirements" title="Functional requirements" class="mw-redirect">functional requirements</a>. In addition to use cases, the SRS also contains nonfunctional (or supplementary) requirements. <a href="/wiki/Non-functional_requirements" title="Non-functional requirements" class="mw-redirect">Non-functional requirements</a> are requirements which impose constraints on the design or implementation (such as <a href="/wiki/Performance_engineering" title="Performance engineering">performance engineering</a> requirements, <a href="/wiki/Quality" title="Quality">quality</a> standards, or design constraints).</p>
<p><br /></p>
<p><a name="General_Outline_of_an_SRS" id="General_Outline_of_an_SRS"></a></p>
